{
  "answer": "**The Falsafa corpus contains poignant laments for lost or ruined civilizations primarily in two works: the Anglo-Saxon elegiac poems collected in *Old English Elegies* and Allama Iqbal's *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*.**[^1][^2]\n\nIn *Old English Elegies* (Medieval, Old English poetry), **Chapter 16 (\"The Ruin\")** meditates on the shattered remnants of a once-great city—likely evoking Roman ruins in Britain—with crumbling giant-built walls, toppled roofs, decayed bath-houses, and vanished feasts, all overtaken by time (Wyrd). The speaker marvels at the contrast between past splendor and present desolation.[^3]\n\nThe same collection's **Chapter 11 (\"The Wanderer\")** evokes a broader sense of civilizational decay: frost-covered walls, crumbling wine-halls, and empty giant-works left after wars, plagues, and slaughters dispersed lords, warriors, and citizens.[^4]\n\nIn **Allama Iqbal's *Bang-E-Dara Part 3* (20th Century, Urdu poetry), Chapter 9 (\"Goristan-e-Shahi,\" or \"The Royal Graveyard\")** is an extended elegy over the tombs of Mughal emperors in Delhi. It grieves fallen empires—Egypt, Babylon, Persia, Rome, and Islam's glory—now reduced to dust and ruins, pondering the transience of nations amid nature's indifference.[^5]\n\nNo other works feature such direct, poetic laments for ruined civilizations. Prose texts (e.g., Charles Comte's *Traité de Législation*) reference historical ruins analytically, without elegiac tone.[^6]\n\n[^1]: /works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/translation/.\n[^2]: /works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/09-goristan-e-shahi/translation/.\n[^3]: /works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/16-wraetlic-is-thes-wealstan-wyrde-yebraecon-burgsted/translation/#p-d0d2bd.\n[^4]: /works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9462cc.\n[^5]: /works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/09-goristan-e-shahi/translation/#p-9890bf.\n[^6]: /works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-iii-ca589a/33-des-relations-observees-entre-l-aristocratie-milit/translation/#p-a2fa72.",
